{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480851"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"117"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/117"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.24,0.71,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3524"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a reduced level of consciousness. Her sister reports that over the last 8 weeks she has seemed more flat and tired and appears to have lost weight. Her sister also noted that she seemed weak and dizzy when cooking in the kitchen recently and had to sit down mid meal preparation. Her medic alert bracelet states \u0022type 1 diabetes mellitus\u0022. Examination shows a tanned woman with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg, pulse 114/min, respiratory rate 16/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 96% on room arm. An arterial blood gas analysis shows pH 7.31 (7.35-7.45), bicarbonate 20 (22-28), CO2 42 mmol/L (34-45) and serum potassium 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0) and glucose 3.8 mmol/L (4.0-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatitis","Severe gastroenteritis","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Addisonian crisis","Hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a metabolic acidosis (low pH, low bicarb, normal CO2) with hyperkalaemia and hypoglycaemia. These are all features of \u003Cstrong\u003EAddisonian crisis\u003C/strong\u003E, and this is consistent with her current reduced conscious state and her preceding weight loss and postural hypotension (dizziness on standing in the kitchen).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatitis \u003C/strong\u003Emost commonly presents with severe, epigastric pain, nausea and vomiting and possible signs of shock in severe cases. It is usually precipitated by alcohol or gallstones. There is also no evidence of risk factors for acute pancreatitis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere gastroenteritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis more likely to present with a number of gastrointestinal symptoms including diarrhoea, abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting, and fever. In severe cases, fluid loss with subsequent electrolyte shifts may create a metabolic acidosis. However, fatigue, weight loss and postural dizziness are not typical features of gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) \u003C/strong\u003Eshould always be considered in patients with Type 1 diabetes mellitus. The key detracting finding is hypoglycaemia (normal/hyperglycaemia is typical in DKA). There is also no evidence of common DKA precipitants in this case (intercurrent illness, ischaemic events, missed insulin etc.).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common complication in diabetes mellitus that may present with reduced consciousness state and fatigue. The key detracting finding is hypoglycaemia (HHS typically has extreme hyperglycaemia with extreme dehydration). Furthermore, HHS is more common in Type 2 diabetes mellitus (although it may still occur with Type 1).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Addisonian crisis should be a key differential in patients presenting with hypotension and a metabolic acidosis."],"references":["Rathbun KM, Nguyen M, Singhal M. Addisonian Crisis. 2020 Dec 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722962.","Feeney C, Buell KG, Avari P, Buckley A, Meeran K, Rees DA. Addisonian crisis: assessment and management. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2018 Mar 2;79(3):C34-C37. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2018.79.3.C34. PMID: 29528741."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"117"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29718"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-03T13:41:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-03T13:41:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"117"}},"conten